<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?><!DOCTYPE collection SYSTEM 'BioC.dtd'><collection><source>PubTator</source><date></date><key>BioC.key</key><document><id>10194471</id><passage><infon key="journal">J. Clin. Invest.; 1999 Apr; 103(7) 989-97</infon><infon key="year">1999</infon><infon key="article-id_pmc">PMC408260</infon><infon key="type">title</infon><infon key="authors">Stafforini DM, Numao T, Tsodikov A, Vaitkus D, Fukuda T, Watanabe N, Fueki N, McIntyre TM, Zimmerman GA, Makino S, Prescott SM</infon><offset>0</offset><text>Deficiency of platelet-activating factor acetylhydrolase is a severity factor for asthma.</text><annotation id="2"><infon key="identifier">7941</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><infon key="NCBI Homologene">3725</infon><location offset="14" length="42"/><text>platelet-activating factor acetylhydrolase</text></annotation><annotation id="3"><infon key="identifier">MESH:D001249</infon><infon key="type">Disease</infon><location offset="82" length="6"/><text>asthma</text></annotation></passage><passage><infon key="type">abstract</infon><offset>90</offset><text>Asthma, a family of airway disorders characterized by airway inflammation, has an increasing incidence worldwide. Platelet-activating factor (PAF) may play a role in the pathophysiology of asthma. Its proinflammatory actions are antagonized by PAF acetylhydrolase. A missense mutation (V279F) in the PAF acetylhydrolase gene results in the complete loss of activity, which occurs in 4% of the Japanese population. We asked if PAF acetylhydrolase deficiency correlates with the incidence and severity of asthma in Japan. We found that the prevalence of PAF acetylhydrolase deficiency is higher in Japanese asthmatics than healthy subjects and that the severity of this syndrome is highest in homozygous-deficient subjects. We conclude that the PAF acetylhydrolase gene is a modulating locus for the severity of asthma.</text><annotation id="15"><infon key="identifier">MESH:D000402</infon><infon key="type">Disease</infon><location offset="110" length="16"/><text>airway disorders</text></annotation><annotation id="16"><infon key="identifier">MESH:D007249</infon><infon key="type">Disease</infon><location offset="151" length="12"/><text>inflammation</text></annotation><annotation id="17"><infon key="identifier">MESH:D001249</infon><infon key="type">Disease</infon><location offset="279" length="6"/><text>asthma</text></annotation><annotation id="18"><infon key="identifier">7941</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><infon key="NCBI Homologene">3725</infon><location offset="334" length="19"/><text>PAF acetylhydrolase</text></annotation><annotation id="19"><infon key="identifier">p.V279F;RS#:76863441</infon><infon key="type">ProteinMutation</infon><location offset="376" length="5"/><text>V279F</text></annotation><annotation id="20"><infon key="identifier">7941</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><infon key="NCBI Homologene">3725</infon><location offset="390" length="19"/><text>PAF acetylhydrolase</text></annotation><annotation id="21"><infon key="identifier">7941</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><infon key="NCBI Homologene">3725</infon><location offset="516" length="19"/><text>PAF acetylhydrolase</text></annotation><annotation id="22"><infon key="identifier">MESH:D001249</infon><infon key="type">Disease</infon><location offset="593" length="6"/><text>asthma</text></annotation><annotation id="23"><infon key="identifier">7941</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><infon key="NCBI Homologene">3725</infon><location offset="642" length="19"/><text>PAF acetylhydrolase</text></annotation><annotation id="24"><infon key="identifier">7941</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><infon key="NCBI Homologene">3725</infon><location offset="833" length="19"/><text>PAF acetylhydrolase</text></annotation><annotation id="25"><infon key="identifier">MESH:D001249</infon><infon key="type">Disease</infon><location offset="900" length="6"/><text>asthma</text></annotation></passage></docum